    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/equivalency-input-parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "The 'Equivalency of input parameters' factor addresses whether the input parameters used in the validation experiment are equivalent to those that will be encountered in the clinical COU — specifically, whether the bovine blood surrogate used in bench testing is a sufficiently faithful proxy for human blood under VAD operating conditions. This factor was considered for assessment under MRL 5 requirements. However, the scoping decision rests on three converging lines of reasoning. First, the FDA generic centrifugal pump is a benchmark geometry used exclusively for V&V method development; it is not itself submitted for regulatory clearance, and the hemolysis model is applied to this geometry only as a credibility demonstration. The equivalency question (bovine surrogate vs. human blood) is therefore a property of the experimental reference dataset rather than a gap in the COU model chain: the same surrogate is used consistently in both validation and the comparative COU assessment, making within-study equivalency tautologically satisfied. Second, the relevant physiological variability in human blood rheology (hematocrit 35–50%, temperature 36.5–37.5 °C, viscosity 3.0–4.5 mPa·s) is fully captured as an uncertain input within the Monte Carlo UQ ensemble (Model Inputs factor, Gradation 4), which propagates this variability through to the hemolysis index prediction interval. The equivalency concern is therefore addressed structurally by the UQ framework rather than requiring a separate factor assessment. Third, conducting a dedicated equivalency study — e.g., paired bovine/human blood hemolysis experiments at all 5 operating points — would require IRB approval for human blood collection and exceeds the scope of the current V&V plan. The scientific risk of not performing this study is bounded by the UQ envelope already established. On balance, the credibility assessment team determined that this factor is appropriately scoped out of the formal assessment: the scientific concern it represents is mitigated by the UQ treatment of blood property variability, and a standalone equivalency assessment would not materially change the overall credibility conclusion at MRL 5. This scoping decision was reviewed and approved by the lead credibility assessor and documented in the project record dated 2026-03-14."
    }
